cellxgene - human kidney dataset contamination

Yuan Yin

2022-09-07

Introduction

In this analysis, we explore the level of contamination of a human kidney scRNASeq dataset using some popular decontamination tools.

# Load packages

library(singleCellTK)
library(celda)
library(ggplot2)
library(scattermore)
library(patchwork)
selectSCTKConda("scar")

c25 <- c(
  "dodgerblue2", "#E31A1C", # red

Import dataset

file.name = '9df60c57-fdf3-4e93-828e-fe9303f20438'

dat_all = importAnnData(
  sampleDirs = '/usr4/spclpgm/yin/cellxgene_benchmark/',
  sampleNames = file.name)

Five donors are included in this dataset. We decontaminate them one at a time.

dat = list()

# Number of cells from each patient
summary(colData(dat_all)$donor_uuid)
## 8c570254-4bef-48d8-bd79-c812f60835a5 5028f75a-8c09-4155-a232-ad7dbfa6042e 
##                                 3683                                 5464 
## 8213a3f7-2437-4e8a-b836-caec33df901d e0def004-9e30-4a3b-9a65-007110f3a1f2 
##                                 3804                                 4114 
## f6c0f811-2fb8-4989-b796-37c14b055517 
##                                 2920
donor_id = levels(colData(dat_all)$donor_uuid)
ndat = length(donor_id)

for(i in 1:ndat){
  dat[[i]] = dat_all[,colData(dat_all)$donor_uuid == donor_id[i]]
}

DecontX

Decontaminate using DecontX. DecontX decontaminate droplets by identifying their cell type specific native distribution and noise distribution. When cell type labels are not provided, a primitive clustering is used to identify cell type. Here since the cell type labels are provided by the dataset, we use that as input to the algorithm.

for(i in 1:ndat){
  dat[[i]] = decontX(dat[[i]], z = colData(dat[[i]])$cell_type)
}

Plot

p1 = list()
p2 = list()
p3 = list()

for (i in 1:ndat){
  sce = dat[[i]]

  umap <- reducedDim(sce, "decontX_UMAP")
  umap.df = data.frame(umap)
  umap.df$cell_type = colData(sce)$cell_type
  umap.df$contam_level = sce$decontX_contamination
  umap.df$mt = colData(sce)$percent.mt
  umap.df$rpl = colData(sce)$percent.rpl
  umap.df$rps = colData(sce)$percent.rps
  umap.df$lib_size = colData(sce)$nCount_SCT


  # UMAP and cell_type
  p1[[i]] = ggplot(umap.df) +
    geom_point(aes(x = DecontX_UMAP_1,
                   y = DecontX_UMAP_2,
                   color = cell_type),
               size = 1.4) +
    ggtitle(paste0('UMAP of donor: ',donor_id[i])) +
    scale_color_manual(values = c25) +
    theme_bw() +
    theme(axis.title.x = element_blank(),
          axis.title.y = element_blank())
  
  # Contamination level
  p2[[i]] = plotDecontXContamination(sce) +
    theme(axis.title.x = element_blank(),
          axis.title.y = element_blank())
  
  
  p3[[i]] = ggplot(umap.df, aes(x = cell_type, y = contam_level, fill = cell_type)) +
  geom_jitter(size = 0.5, color = 'gray') +
  geom_violin(alpha = 0.7, scale = 'width') +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c25) +
  ylab('Percentage') +
  ggtitle(paste0('Contamination percentage by cell_type. donor: ',donor_id[i])) +
    coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0, 1)) + 
  theme_bw() +
  theme(axis.title.x = element_blank(),
        legend.position = 'none',
        axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45,vjust = 0.6))
  

}

UMAP and contamination level

Visualize the droplets of each patients and their contamination level.

UMAP is generated using droplets’ RNASeq profile and we can see that it is generally in agreement with the cell_type label coming with the dataset.
